== Japanese content ==
{{特殊文字}}
'''Nyuu Shrine''' (にゅうじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|lt=Nagahama|Q844130|WD=Q844130|1=Nagahama, Shiga}}, {{ill|lt=Shiga Prefecture|Q131358|WD=Q131358|1=Shiga Prefecture}}. Since there are two shrines of the same name in the city, they are treated here as upper and lower sections.

=== Nyuu Shrine [Kami-Nyuu] ===
{{神社
|名称   = Nyuu Shrine
|画像   = [[File:Nyu-jinja (Kaminyu) 202308-1.jpg|270px]]<br />Torii
|所在地 = {{ill|lt=Shiga Prefecture|Q131358|WD=Q131358|1=Shiga Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Nagahama|Q844130|WD=Q844130|1=Nagahama, Shiga}}Yogo-cho Kami-Nyuu 378
|位置   = {{ウィキ座標2段度分秒|35|33|53.0|N|136|14|02.4|E|scale:25000}}
|祭神   = Niutsuhime-no-Mikoto<br/>{{ill|lt=Mizuhanome|Q8191796|WD=Q8191796|lt=Mitsuhanome-no-Mikoto|1=Mizuhanome}}
|社格   = {{ill|lt=Shikinaisha small shrine|Q134917287|WD=Q134917287|1=Shikinai Shosha}} / former {{ill|lt=Village Shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}
|創建   = (trad.) reign of {{ill|lt=Emperor Tenmu|Q335181|WD=Q335181|1=Emperor Tenmu}}
|本殿   = {{ill|lt=nagare-zukuri|Q210684|WD=Q210684|lt=two-bay nagare-zukuri|1=Nagare-zukuri}}
|別名   = 
|札所等 = 
|例祭   = {{ill|lt=April 3|Q2509|WD=Q2509|1=April 3}}
|神事   = Hikiyama Tea Bowl Festival (April 2)
|地図   = {{Location map|Japan Shiga|label=Nyuu Shrine|coordinates=
{{coord2|35|33|53.0|N|136|14|02.4|E|}}|position=bottom|width=200|mark=Shinto torii icon vermillion.svg|marksize=15|float=center|caption=}}
{{maplink2|frame=yes|plain=yes|type=point|zoom=9|marker=religious-shinto|frame-align=center|frame-width=200|frame-height=250|coord={{coord|35|33|53.0|N|136|14|02.4|E}}}}
}}

It is enshrined in Yogo-cho Kami-Nyuu. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Engishiki shrine|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286|lt=Shikinaisha}} {{ill|lt=disputed identification shrine|Q135022904|WD=Q135022904|1=Shikinai Ronsha}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
*{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Niutsuhime-no-Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}}
*{{ill|lt=Mizuhanome|Q8191796|WD=Q8191796|lt=Mitsuhanome-no-Mikoto|1=Mizuhanome}}

=== Shrine crest ===
Circular mountain and water motif.

=== History ===
According to shrine tradition, around the time of {{ill|lt=Emperor Tenmu|Q335181|WD=Q335181|1=Emperor Tenmu}}, Nyuu no Mahito enshrined the Nyuu deity on Mt. Tanbono. It is said to have been moved to the present site in {{ill|lt=764|Q31163|WD=Q31163|1=764}} ({{ill|lt=Tenpyo-hoji|Q1346307|WD=Q1346307|1=Tenpyō-hōji}} 8). The current shrine buildings are said to have been rebuilt in {{ill|lt=1663|Q7577|WD=Q7577|1=1663}} ({{ill|lt=Kanbun|Q1146228|WD=Q1146228|1=Kanbun (era)}} 3). Former {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=village shrine|1=UNKNOWN}}.

=== Festivals ===
* Okonai - January 7
* Hikiyama Tea Bowl Festival - April 2
* Annual festival - April 3
* Nogami Festival - August 23

=== Shrine outside precincts ===
* Hachiman Shrine
* Ebisu Shrine

=== Sacred grove ===
The surrounding area is designated as the "Nyuu Shrine Sacred Grove" under Shiga Prefecture's green environment conservation zones (area 1.78 ha; designated on August 30, 1989)<ref>{{Cite web|和書|date= |url=https://www.pref.shiga.lg.jp/file/attachment/21417.pdf |title=Shiga Environment 2009 |publisher=Shiga Prefecture |accessdate=2025-04-11}}</ref>.

=== Nyuu Shrine [Shimo-Nyuu] ===
{{神社
|名称   = Nyuu Shrine
|画像   = [[File:Nyu-jinja (Shimonyu) 202308-1.jpg|270px]]<br />Torii
|所在地 = Shiga Prefecture, Nagahama, Yogo-cho Shimo-Nyuu 1087
|位置   = {{ウィキ座標2段度分秒|35|33|24.8|N|136|13|40.8|E|scale:25000}}
|祭神   = {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Takaokami|1=UNKNOWN}}<br />Niutsuhime-no-Mikoto
|社格   = {{ill|lt=Shikinaisha small shrine|Q134917287|WD=Q134917287|1=Shikinai Shosha}} / former {{ill|lt=Village Shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}
|創建   = (trad.) {{ill|lt=Tenpyo-hoji|Q1346307|WD=Q1346307|1=Tenpyō-hōji}} 8
|本殿   = {{ill|lt=nagare-zukuri|Q210684|WD=Q210684|lt=one-bay nagare-zukuri|1=Nagare-zukuri}}
|別名   = 
|札所等 = 
|例祭   = {{ill|lt=April 3|Q2509|WD=Q2509|1=April 3}}
|神事   = Head Rite (January 2)
|地図   = {{Location map|Japan Shiga|label=Nyuu Shrine|coordinates=
{{coord2|35|33|24.8|N|136|13|40.8|E|}}|position=bottom|width=200|mark=Shinto torii icon vermillion.svg|marksize=15|float=center|caption=}}
{{maplink2|frame=yes|plain=yes|type=point|zoom=9|marker=religious-shinto|frame-align=center|frame-width=200|frame-height=250|coord={{coord|35|33|24.8|N|136|13|40.8|E}}}}
}}

It is enshrined in Yogo-cho Shimo-Nyuu. Like Kami-Nyuu, it is a disputed identification of an Engishiki shrine.

=== Enshrined deities ===
*{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Takaokami|1=UNKNOWN}}
*{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Niutsuhime-no-Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}}

=== History ===
According to shrine tradition, it was founded in {{ill|lt=764|Q31163|WD=Q31163|1=764}} ({{ill|lt=Tenpyo-hoji|Q1346307|WD=Q1346307|1=Tenpyō-hōji}} 8). At the time of enshrinement it stood at the foot of Mt. Nyuho-Takayama, but it was moved to the present site in {{ill|lt=870|Q23629|WD=Q23629|1=870}} ({{ill|lt=Jogan (Japan)|Q1075635|WD=Q1075635|lt=Jogan|1=Jōgan}} 12). The former site still has a small shrine known as Kagurano Myojin. The current shrine buildings are said to have been rebuilt in {{ill|lt=1667|Q7588|WD=Q7588|1=1667}} ({{ill|lt=Kanbun|Q1146228|WD=Q1146228|1=Kanbun (era)}} 7). It was ranked as a {{ill|lt=Village Shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}} in {{ill|lt=1876|Q7766|WD=Q7766|1=1876}} ({{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 9).

=== Festivals ===
* Hana-no-kashira - January 2
* Hana-no-kashira - January 6
* O-gashira - January 14-15
* Annual festival - April 3

=== Precinct shrines ===
* Ebisu Shrine
* Inari Shrine

